{
    float sum = 0.0f;
    for(int w = 0; w < kBlockSize / kWavefront; w++)
    {
        sum += s_row_sq_sum[row * kWavefront + w];
    }
    s_row_sq_sum[row] = sum;
}
```

For row 0, this sums s_row_sq_sum[0], s_row_sq_sum[1], s_row_sq_sum[2], s_row_sq_sum[3], which are the first 4 elements. But the wavefront leaders wrote to positions 0, 64, 128, 192 - not consecutive indices. I need to fix the indexing so the second reduction actually combines the wavefront partial sums correctly.

The wavefront leaders should write to s_row_sq_sum[row * num_wavefronts + wavefront_id] instead. Since there are 4 wavefronts and 4 rows, I need to map each (row, wavefront) pair to the right shared memory location.

Rather than trying to pack everything into one array, I could use a simpler approach: have each wavefront leader accumulate its partial sum directly into the final result, then reduce across wavefronts in a second step.

Alternatively, I could use a straightforward sequential reduction where threads iterate through the shared memory array to sum all values for each row. This avoids the complexity of coordinating across wavefronts and is easier to reason about.

The simplest approach is to have each thread contribute its partial sum to shared memory, then use a single thread to perform the final reduction across all contributions for each row.

```cpp
__shared__ float s_row_sq_sum[kMaxRowsPerTile];

// Each thread accumulates its local sum of squares
for(int row = 0; row < kRowsPerTile; row++) {
